[1]
Date: 16 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters via Times of Tibet, 16 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.timesoftibet.com/artman/publish/article_1007.shtml>


China says deadly bird flu reaches remote Tibet
-----------------------------------------------
China's Ministry of Agriculture said on Monday the H5N1 avian flu virus had
been found in the Himalayan region's capital, Lhasa, about 3600 metres (11
800 ft) above sea level.

Other outbreaks, which in China have so far been limited to flocks of
chickens and other poultry, were reported in the southern province of
Guangdong and the central province of Hubei, the ministry said on its Web
site.

The ministry did not say how the virus was thought to have made its way to
Tibet, one of China's poorest regions, which is home to about 2.7 million
people and is famed for its Buddhist tradition. 15 of China's 31 provinces
and major cities have confirmed outbreaks of the avian influenza that has
killed 14 Vietnamese and 6 Thais and led to the culling of millions of
poultry in 8 Asian countries.

